
  <sn><md>### Weathering of Feldspar

On the basis of the `difference in cleavage angles`, feldspars are divided into two primary groups:

* A. `Ortho`clase
* B. `Plagio`clase

Under the influence of `hydration` and `carbonation`, feldspar breaks down into clay minerals like kaolinite and others.<br>
$\text{feldspar} \xrightarrow{\text{hydration,carbonation}} \text{clay minerals}$</md></sn><sn><md>#### A. Orthoclase Group

**General Decomposition Pathway**
The schematic chemical equations representing the step-by-step and overall decomposition of orthoclase feldspar are as follows:

$$\begin{aligned} &amp;\text{Hydrolysis:} &amp;&amp; \mathrm{KAlSi_3O_8 + HOH \xrightarrow{\text{hydrolysis}} HAlSi_3O_8\ (Acid\ silicate) + KOH} \\ &amp;\text{Hydration:} &amp;&amp; \mathrm{HAlSi_3O_8 + HOH \xrightarrow{\text{hydration}} H_4Al_2Si_2O_9 + SiO_2} \\ &amp;\text{Carbonation:} &amp;&amp; \mathrm{KOH + CO_2 \xrightarrow{\text{carbonation}} K_2CO_3 + H_2O} \\ \hline &amp;\text{Overall Equation:} &amp;&amp; \mathrm{KAlSi_3O_8\ (Orthoclase\ feldspar) + CO_2 + H_2O \longrightarrow H_4Al_2Si_2O_9 + SiO_2 + K_2CO_3} \end{aligned}$$

**Extreme Weathering Conditions**
In extreme climatic conditions, such as in humid tropics and subtropics, the resulting kaolinite ($\mathrm{H_4Al_2Si_2O_9}$) decomposes further into oxides of Aluminium ($\mathrm{Al}$) and Silicon ($\mathrm{Si}$):

$$\mathrm{H_4Al_2Si_2O_9 \xrightarrow{\text{high temp.}} Al_2O_3 + SiO_2 + H_2O}$$

**Acidic Environments**
Under acid conditions, orthoclase transitions into montmorillonite:
$\text{kaolinite} \xrightarrow{\text{acidic env}} \text{montmorillonite}$

$$\mathrm{KAlSi_3O_8 \longrightarrow Al_4Si_8O_{20}(OH)_2\ (Montmorillonite)}$$
</md></sn>
