<sn><md>#### B. Plagioclase Group

The important minerals belonging to this group are `albite` ($\mathrm{Na}$-rich), `anorthite` ($\mathrm{Ca}$-rich), and `oligoclase`.



::: .p-2 border mb-3

##### Albite ($\mathrm{NaAlSi_3O_8}$)

**Decomposition Steps**

$$\begin{aligned} &amp;\text{Hydrolysis:} &amp;&amp; \mathrm{NaAlSi_3O_8 + HOH \xrightarrow{\text{hydrolysis}} HAlSi_3O_8\ (Acid\ silicate) + NaOH} \\ &amp;\text{Hydration:} &amp;&amp; \mathrm{HAlSi_3O_8 + HOH \xrightarrow{\text{hydration}} H_4Al_2Si_2O_9 + SiO_2} \\ &amp;\text{Carbonation:} &amp;&amp; \mathrm{NaOH + CO_2 \xrightarrow{\text{carbonation}} Na_2CO_3 + H_2O} \\ \hline &amp;\text{Overall Equation:} &amp;&amp; \mathrm{NaAlSi_3O_8 + CO_2 + H_2O \longrightarrow H_4Al_2Si_2O_9 + SiO_2 + Na_2CO_3} \end{aligned}$$

**Environmental Variations**

* **Extreme Climatic Conditions:** In humid tropics, `kaolinite` will split into its `constituent parts`:

$$\mathrm{H_4Al_2Si_2O_9 \xrightarrow{\text{high temp.}} Al_2O_3 + SiO_2 + H_2O}$$


* **Acidic Conditions:**

$$\mathrm{NaAlSi_3O_8 \longrightarrow Al_4Si_8O_{20}(OH)_2\ (Montmorillonite)}$$


* **Association with Orthoclase:** When `albite` is associated with `orthoclase`, `muscovite` is formed: (albite + orthoclase = muscovite)

$$\mathrm{NaAlSi_3O_8 + KAlSi_3O_8 + CO_2 + H_2O \longrightarrow KAl_2(AlSi_3)O_{10}(OH)_2\ (Muscovite) + SiO_2 + (Na, K)_2CO_3}$$
:::


::: .p-2 border

##### Anorthite ($\mathrm{CaAl_2Si_2O_8}$)

Straight `carbonation of anorthite` ultimately produces `kaolinite and calcium carbonate`:

$$\begin{aligned} &amp;\mathrm{CaAl_2Si_2O_8 + CO_2 + H_2O \longrightarrow H_4Al_2Si_2O_9 + CaCO_3} \\ &amp;\mathrm{CaCO_3 + H_2CO_3 \longrightarrow Ca(HCO_3)_2} \end{aligned}$$

* **Extreme Climatic Conditions:** In high-temperature humid tropics, the secondary kaolinite breaks down further:

$$\mathrm{H_4Al_2Si_2O_9 \xrightarrow{\text{high temp.}} Al_2O_3 + SiO_2 + H_2O}$$

:::</md></sn>